    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="project-hero">
        <h1>Did the 2022-2024 Inflation Wave Hit Women Harder?</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Headline UK consumer price inflation peaked at 11.1% in October 2022 and stayed above
            the 2% target until mid-2024. Aggregate figures hide who actually paid more. This
            project uses monthly item-level price quotes from the ONS Consumer Prices Index
            collection to estimate whether the prices women face rose faster than the prices men
            face, separating two distinct mechanisms: prices on the same item moving differently
            for gendered variants, and women's consumption baskets weighting more heavily toward
            categories that inflated faster. A companion analysis to
            <a href="page.html">the cross-sectional pink tax study</a>, this piece focuses on
            change rather than level.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
            Status: methodology and item mapping fixed; empirical results pending data download
            and pipeline run.
        </p>
    </section>


    <!-- BACKGROUND -->
    <section id="overview">
        <span class="section-label">Background</span>
        <h2>Concepts &amp; Research Design</h2>

        <p>
            <strong>Headline inflation</strong> is the percentage change in a single aggregate
            price index, typically the Consumer Prices Index (CPI), constructed by weighting
            thousands of individual goods and services by their share in average household
            spending. The ONS publishes the headline number every month. By construction, the
            headline figure is a single rate for the average household; it does not say how
            inflation was distributed across different types of consumers.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Inflation incidence</strong> is the study of who actually faced the highest
            price increases. Households consume different baskets: families with young children
            spend more on nappies and baby formula, retirees more on healthcare and energy,
            single-adult women more on personal care and clothing relative to men. If the
            categories that inflated fastest happen to be concentrated in one group's basket,
            that group experienced higher effective inflation than the headline rate suggests.
            Cardoso, Ferreira, Leiva-Leon and Shahid (2024) document substantial cross-household
            dispersion in effective inflation rates during the 2022 wave across the euro area.
            The UK question, and specifically the gender cut, has had less attention.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>The 2022-2024 episode</strong> was driven primarily by energy and food, with
            second-round effects spreading into services. Personal care items inflated in
            different ways depending on the input mix: products with high agricultural or
            chemical content tracked food inflation; imported cosmetics tracked exchange rate and
            shipping costs; services such as haircuts tracked wage growth. Whether these factors
            washed out across genders, or whether they concentrated in one direction, is the
            empirical question.
        </p>

        <div class="divider"><span>Research Question</span></div>

        <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: var(--navy); font-weight: 600; text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto 2.5rem;">
            Did cumulative price growth between January 2022 and December 2024 differ
            systematically between female-coded, male-coded, and gender-neutral consumer goods
            and services in the UK? If so, was the difference driven by basket composition or by
            within-item price movements?
        </p>

        <p>
            The two channels matter for different reasons. A <strong>within-item gap</strong>,
            where the same razor blades or shampoo bottle rose faster in one gendered variant
            than the other, points to firm-level pricing decisions and is a more direct test of
            differential pricing power. A <strong>basket-composition gap</strong>, where prices
            rose similarly within each item but the typical female basket contained more items
            from fast-inflating categories, is closer to a welfare statement about consumer
            exposure: it answers "how much did the cost of being a typical female consumer rise
            versus a typical male consumer", regardless of why.
        </p>

        <div class="divider"><span>Analytical Approach</span></div>

        <p>
            Three specifications, in order of increasing welfare relevance and decreasing
            within-item identification:
        </p>

        <ol style="max-width: 760px; margin: 0 0 1.5rem 1rem; line-height: 1.7;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
                <strong>Within-item difference-in-differences.</strong> A panel of monthly price
                observations with item fixed effects and month fixed effects, identifying the
                female premium in cumulative price growth from the cross-item variation. This is
                the cleanest specification: it absorbs all baseline price differences between
                items.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
                <strong>Basket-weighted price indices.</strong> Two Laspeyres indices constructed
                from the same monthly quotes, one weighted by single-female-adult expenditure
                shares from the Living Costs and Food Survey (LCFS), the other by
                single-male-adult shares. Cumulative inflation is read directly from the index
                levels.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
                <strong>Unit-price specification for shrinkflation.</strong> Where pack size is
                available in the quote, repeat the within-item DiD on log unit price (price per
                100g, per item, per ml) rather than headline price. If shrinkflation was
                gender-asymmetric, this specification will detect it.
            </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
            A within-between decomposition then partitions the basket-weighted gap into the
            share explained by differential within-item inflation and the share explained by
            differential basket composition. This is the analogue to the composition versus
            within-category decomposition that drove the cross-sectional pink tax finding.
        </p>
    </section>


    <!-- DATA -->
    <section>
        <span class="section-label">Data</span>
        <h2>Sources &amp; Preparation</h2>

        <p>
            Three datasets, all freely downloadable from ONS, with no scraping and no access
            request required.
        </p>

        <div class="two-col">
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">CPI price quotes microdata</h4>
                <p>
                    Monthly CSVs of individual price quotes used to construct the headline CPI.
                    Each row is one observation: item code, base price, current price,
                    NUTS-1 region, validity marker, stratum weight, shop type. Coverage runs from
                    February 1996 to the latest month. Personal care quotes (Division 12) will
                    continue to be published after the March 2026 introduction of grocery scanner
                    data, which only removes Division 1 and 2 quotes.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">CPI item indices</h4>
                <p>
                    Pre-computed item-level price indices (one number per item per month). Used
                    as a sanity check on the constructed basket indices and to fill any items
                    where price quotes are unavailable. Replaced in March 2025 by "consumption
                    segment indices" with the same structure but slightly broader item
                    definitions.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Living Costs and Food Survey (LCFS)</h4>
                <p>
                    Annual ONS household expenditure survey. Provides expenditure shares by
                    household type, including single male adult and single female adult
                    households. Used to construct gender-specific basket weights at the COICOP
                    division level, then disaggregated to item level using within-division CPI
                    weights.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Sample window</h4>
                <p>
                    Pre-period: January 2019 to December 2021 (baseline, pre-inflation wave).
                    Treatment period: January 2022 to December 2024 (the wave). This gives 72
                    monthly observations per item, three years on each side of the structural
                    break.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Item Coding</h3>

        <p>
            Items are coded female, male, or neutral based on the ONS item description. The
            coding rules are mechanical: an item is female-coded if its description references
            a product or service primarily marketed to women (mascara, foundation, women's
            hair colourant, women's haircut, manicure); male-coded if explicitly male (men's
            haircut, electric razor, razor cartridge blades, which are sold predominantly to men
            in the ONS basket); neutral otherwise. Ambiguous cases (deodorant, shampoo,
            shower gel) are coded neutral. The female and male codings together cover roughly
            two dozen items; the neutral category is large but only serves as a reference group
            and a placebo check.
        </p>

        <h3>Item Mapping</h3>

        <p>
            The table below lists the items used in the analysis with their ONS item reference
            numbers. The coding is fixed in advance, not selected to produce any particular
            result.
        </p>

        <table class="results-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th style="text-align: left;">Item ID</th>
                    <th style="text-align: left;">ONS Description</th>
                    <th style="text-align: left;">Coding</th>
                    <th style="text-align: left;">Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td class="num">520206</td><td>Tampons, pack of 10-20</td><td>Female</td><td>Replaced by 520256 in Feb 2023</td></tr>
                <tr><td class="num">520256</td><td>Sanitary towels</td><td>Female</td><td>Continuation of 520206</td></tr>
                <tr><td class="num">520223</td><td>Mascara</td><td>Female</td><td></td></tr>
                <tr><td class="num">520236</td><td>Women's hair colourant 60-140ml</td><td>Female</td><td></td></tr>
                <tr><td class="num">520243</td><td>Liquid foundation 30-35ml</td><td>Female</td><td></td></tr>
