        <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-muted);">
            Sources: ONS CPI basket item descriptions, Dec 2019 to Jun 2024 release; ONS FOI
            response on tampon and sanitary towel item reference numbers.
        </p>

        <div class="note-box" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
            <h4>The tampon-sanitary-towel break</h4>
            <p>
                In February 2023 ONS replaced item 520206 (tampons) with item 520256 (sanitary
                towels) in the CPI basket, with no overlap month. The within-item DiD treats
                these as a single bridged "period products" item, with a level shift dummy at the
                bridge date to absorb any compositional change between the two products. A
                robustness check drops the bridged item entirely and confirms results are not
                driven by this single category. The bridge falls inside the inflation wave, so
                this is an unavoidable design choice.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- PART I: WITHIN-ITEM DiD -->
    <section id="within-item" class="summary-section full-width-section">
        <div class="container">
            <span class="section-label">Part I</span>
            <h2>Within-Item Inflation Differential</h2>

            <p>
                The first specification estimates whether cumulative price growth on
                female-coded items differed from male-coded and neutral items, holding item
                identity fixed. The estimating equation is:
            </p>

            <div class="note-box" style="font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.95rem; text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
                log(p<sub>iqt</sub>) = &alpha;<sub>i</sub> + &gamma;<sub>t</sub>
                + &beta;<sub>F</sub> &middot; (female<sub>i</sub> &times; post<sub>t</sub>)
                + &beta;<sub>M</sub> &middot; (male<sub>i</sub> &times; post<sub>t</sub>)
                + &epsilon;<sub>iqt</sub>
            </div>

            <p>
                Here p<sub>iqt</sub> is the price quote for item <em>i</em>, observation
                <em>q</em>, in month <em>t</em>. The item fixed effects &alpha;<sub>i</sub>
                absorb every time-invariant feature of an item: its baseline price, its category,
                whether it is a service or a good. The month fixed effects &gamma;<sub>t</sub>
                absorb common shocks: overall inflation, VAT changes, seasonal patterns. The
                coefficient &beta;<sub>F</sub> measures the cumulative log price growth on
                female-coded items relative to neutral items during the post-2022 period;
                &beta;<sub>M</sub> does the same for male items. Standard errors are clustered at
                the item level, since shocks within an item are correlated across months.
            </p>

            <p>
                A more flexible version replaces the single post-2022 dummy with month-by-month
                interactions, tracing out the trajectory of the female-neutral gap over time.
                This produces an event-study chart showing whether any gendered divergence built
                gradually or emerged sharply at a particular point in the wave.
            </p>

            <div class="viz-container">
                <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 4rem 1rem; background: var(--grey-100); border-radius: 4px;">
                    Event study: cumulative log price growth on female-coded items relative to
                    neutral items, monthly from Jan 2019 to Dec 2024.<br>
                    <em>Chart will be inserted here once the pipeline has been run on downloaded
                    ONS data.</em>
                </p>
            </div>

            <h3>Coefficient table</h3>

            <div class="viz-container">
                <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 3rem 1rem; background: var(--grey-100); border-radius: 4px;">
                    Specifications (1) base DiD, (2) + region FE, (3) + shop type FE,
                    (4) restricted to goods only, (5) restricted to services only.<br>
                    <em>Table will be inserted here once the pipeline has been run.</em>
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="note-box">
                <h4>What to expect ex ante</h4>
                <p>
                    Two priors. First, services items (haircuts, manicures) likely tracked wage
                    growth, which ran roughly 5-6% annually during 2022-2024 in the UK; women's
                    services use longer appointment times, which may amplify the wage pass-through.
                    Second, goods items with high agricultural or chemical input shares (cosmetics
                    with palm oil derivatives, hair products) likely tracked commodity prices
                    closely. Whether these effects net out across the female and male coding is
                    the empirical question. The cross-sectional pink tax results suggested no
                    systematic level gap within categories, so any divergence here is genuinely
                    about the inflation wave, not about long-running discrimination.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- PART II: BASKET INDICES -->
    <section id="baskets">
        <span class="section-label">Part II</span>
        <h2>Basket-Weighted Inflation</h2>

        <p>
            The second specification asks the welfare question directly: how much did the cost
            of the typical female basket rise versus the typical male basket? This requires
            attaching expenditure weights to each item and aggregating into two parallel price
            indices.
        </p>

        <h3>Index construction</h3>

        <p>
            A <strong>Laspeyres index</strong> measures the cost of a fixed reference basket at
            current prices, expressed as a ratio of the same basket valued at base-period
            prices. The reference basket is set in the base period (January 2022 in this design)
            and held constant; the index value at month <em>t</em> shows how expensive that
            same basket would be if purchased in month <em>t</em>. Formally:
        </p>

        <div class="note-box" style="font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.95rem; text-align: center; padding: 1.5rem;">
            L<sub>t</sub><sup>g</sup> = &Sigma;<sub>i</sub> w<sub>i</sub><sup>g</sup> &middot;
            (p<sub>it</sub> / p<sub>i0</sub>) &times; 100
        </div>

        <p>
            where <em>g</em> indexes the gender basket (female or male), w<sub>i</sub><sup>g</sup>
            is the expenditure share of item <em>i</em> in basket <em>g</em>, derived from LCFS
            single-adult household data, p<sub>it</sub> is the price of item <em>i</em> at
            month <em>t</em> (the unweighted mean across quote observations), and p<sub>i0</sub>
            is its base-period price.
        </p>

        <p>
            A <strong>Tornqvist index</strong> uses a geometric average of base-period and
            current-period expenditure shares as weights, which is more robust to the fact that
            consumers substitute away from items that have become relatively more expensive.
            Both indices are reported; the Laspeyres figure is the main one, and the Tornqvist
            serves as a robustness check.
        </p>

        <h3>Headline result</h3>

        <div class="project-meta-bar" style="margin: 2rem 0;">
            <div class="meta-item">
                <span class="meta-label">Female basket Jan 2022</span>
                <span class="meta-value">100.0</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta-item">
                <span class="meta-label">Female basket Dec 2024</span>
                <span class="meta-value">pending</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta-item">
                <span class="meta-label">Male basket Dec 2024</span>
                <span class="meta-value">pending</span>
            </div>
            <div class="meta-item">
                <span class="meta-label">Basket gap (F - M)</span>
                <span class="meta-value">pending</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="viz-container">
            <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 4rem 1rem; background: var(--grey-100); border-radius: 4px;">
                Laspeyres price index for female and male single-adult baskets, monthly,
                Jan 2022 = 100.<br>
                <em>Chart will be inserted here once the pipeline has been run.</em>
            </p>
        </div>

        <h3>Within-between decomposition</h3>

        <p>
            The gap between the two basket indices can be decomposed into two parts. The
            <strong>within-item component</strong> captures the contribution of differential
            inflation on the same items: items appearing in both baskets but with different
            rates of price growth. The <strong>between-item component</strong> captures the
            contribution of basket composition: female-coded items inflated similarly to
            male-coded ones, but the female basket weighted them more heavily, or vice versa.
            The decomposition is the same logic as the within-category versus composition split
            in the cross-sectional pink tax analysis.
        </p>

        <div class="viz-container">
            <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 3rem 1rem; background: var(--grey-100); border-radius: 4px;">
                Decomposition table: total gap, within-item share, between-item share.<br>
                <em>Table will be inserted here once the pipeline has been run.</em>
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- PART III: SHRINKFLATION -->
    <section id="shrinkflation">
        <span class="section-label">Part III</span>
        <h2>Shrinkflation</h2>

        <p>
            <strong>Shrinkflation</strong> describes pack-size reductions that hold headline
            price approximately constant while reducing the quantity delivered, so the per-unit
            price rises without the shelf price moving. UK supermarket personal care saw notable
            shrinkflation activity through 2022-2024, with media coverage suggesting smaller-pack
            categories were disproportionately affected. Smaller packs are more common in female
            personal care (cosmetics in small bottles, applicators) than in male personal care
            (shaving foam, deodorant in larger formats). If shrinkflation was concentrated in
            smaller-pack items, it may have widened any female-male inflation gap beyond what
            shelf price comparisons reveal.
        </p>

        <p>
            The ONS price quote file includes pack size in the item description (and explicitly
            in some quote fields when present). Constructing unit prices (price per gram, price
            per item, price per ml depending on the product) and re-running the within-item DiD
            on log unit price will reveal whether shrinkflation contributed asymmetrically.
            Where pack size is not parseable from the quote, the item is dropped from this
            specification.
        </p>

        <div class="viz-container">
            <p style="text-align: center; color: var(--text-muted); padding: 4rem 1rem; background: var(--grey-100); border-radius: 4px;">
                Within-item DiD on log headline price versus log unit price, female and male
                coefficients side by side.<br>
                <em>Chart will be inserted here once the pipeline has been run.</em>
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- CONCLUSIONS placeholder -->
    <section id="conclusions" style="padding-bottom: 2.5rem;">
        <span class="section-label">Synthesis</span>
        <h2>Conclusions</h2>
        <p style="max-width: 760px; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; color: var(--text-muted); font-style: italic;">
            Conclusions will be written once empirical results are in. The structure below
            lists the questions the analysis is designed to answer; specific findings will be
            inserted in place of the question text.
        </p>

        <div class="conclusion-grid">
            <div class="conclusion-card">
                <div class="conclusion-number">01</div>
                <div class="conclusion-content">
                    <h4>Was there a within-item gender inflation gap?</h4>
                    <p>
                        From the DiD specification, does &beta;<sub>F</sub> &minus;
                        &beta;<sub>M</sub> differ significantly from zero? If yes, in which
                        direction and by how much?
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="conclusion-card">
                <div class="conclusion-number">02</div>
                <div class="conclusion-content">
                    <h4>Was there a basket-weighted gender inflation gap?</h4>
                    <p>
                        From the Laspeyres indices, how much did the female basket rise relative
                        to the male basket over Jan 2022 to Dec 2024? Is the answer robust to
                        Tornqvist weighting?
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="conclusion-card">
                <div class="conclusion-number">03</div>
                <div class="conclusion-content">
                    <h4>Which channel dominated?</h4>
                    <p>
                        Of the total basket gap, what share is explained by within-item inflation
                        differences and what share by basket composition? The cross-sectional
                        pink tax piece found composition dominated; the inflation question may
                        follow the same pattern or break it.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="conclusion-card">
                <div class="conclusion-number">04</div>
                <div class="conclusion-content">
                    <h4>Did shrinkflation matter?</h4>
                    <p>
                        How does the DiD coefficient on log unit price compare with the
                        coefficient on log headline price? A larger unit-price coefficient
                        indicates shrinkflation contributed to gendered exposure.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- LIMITATIONS -->
    <section>
        <h2>Limitations</h2>

        <div class="two-col">
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Item-level coverage</h4>
                <p>
                    The ONS basket is a representative sample, not an exhaustive product list.
                    Only a small number of items are explicitly gendered (around a dozen on each
                    side). The neutral category is large but contributes mainly as a reference
                    group. Stronger statements require more items per side, which the public
                    quote data does not provide.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Basket weight precision</h4>
                <p>
                    LCFS expenditure shares are reported at COICOP division and group level, not
                    at individual item level. Disaggregating to item weights uses within-group
                    CPI weights, which are not gender-specific. The basket indices therefore
                    capture differences in division-level spending allocations, not within-group
                    variation in product choice.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Item continuity</h4>
                <p>
                    The tampon to sanitary towel bridge in February 2023 sits inside the
                    inflation wave. The pipeline treats them as a continued series with a level
                    shift dummy, but a structural change in product mix between the two ONS
                    items is possible. A robustness check excludes the bridged item.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="note-box">
                <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Coding subjectivity</h4>
                <p>
                    Items are coded female, male, or neutral based on ONS description text and
                    typical use. Deodorant and shampoo are coded neutral here despite often being
                    sold in gendered variants in supermarkets. A more permissive coding (treating
                    deodorant as gendered) would change the sample but not the within-item
                    identification.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>


    <!-- METHODOLOGICAL NOTES -->
    <section id="methods" class="summary-section full-width-section">
        <div class="container">
            <h2>Methodological Notes</h2>

            <div class="two-col">
                <div class="note-box">
                    <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Data pipeline</h4>
                    <p>
                        Stage 1: download 72 monthly ONS price quote CSVs (Jan 2019 to Dec 2024)
                        from the ONS website. Stage 2: filter to the personal care item set
                        listed above, attach gender coding. Stage 3: parse pack size from item
                        description where possible. Stage 4: assemble item-month panel. Stage 5:
                        run DiD and basket index specifications. All steps in a single Python
                        script with checkpointed intermediates.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="note-box">
                    <h4 style="color: var(--accent);">Statistical methods</h4>
                    <p>
                        Within-item DiD: OLS with two-way fixed effects (item, month), standard
                        errors clustered at item level using linearmodels.PanelOLS. Event study:
                        same model with month-by-treatment interactions. Basket indices:
                        Laspeyres and Tornqvist with January 2022 base. Decomposition: Oaxaca-
                        Blinder-style split into within-item and between-item components.
                        Robustness: drop bridged items, restrict to goods only, restrict to
                        services only, alternative codings.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div id="skills-tags" style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; justify-content: center; gap: 0.75rem; margin: 2.5rem 0;"></div>
        </div>
    </section>


